#Creates NetworkX Multigraph for calculations
#Edges retain information about length, voltage and number of circuits

import networkx as nx
import numpy as np
from scipy.sparse import load_npz

# Load the sparse matrices
lengths = load_npz('/Users/kobabendiks/Desktop/UNI/Bachelor Thesis/Datasets/Transmission/entsoe/Links Edited/Matrices/PowerLinesMatrix_length.npz')
voltages = load_npz('/Users/kobabendiks/Desktop/UNI/Bachelor Thesis/Datasets/Transmission/entsoe/Links Edited/Matrices/PowerLinesMatrix_voltage.npz')
circuits = load_npz('/Users/kobabendiks/Desktop/UNI/Bachelor Thesis/Datasets/Transmission/entsoe/Links Edited/Matrices/PowerLinesMatrix_circuits.npz')

# Create an empty MultiGraph to support multiple edges between nodes
G = nx.MultiGraph()

# Convert node ID to label (row;col format)
def node_id_to_label(node_id, grid_width=5563):
    row = node_id // grid_width
    col = node_id % grid_width
    return f"[{row};{col}]"

# Add edges to the graph, skipping mirrored duplicates
for i in range(lengths.nnz):
    src = lengths.row[i]
    dst = lengths.col[i]
    
    # Skip one direction of symmetric matrix (to avoid duplication)
    if src < dst:
        label_src = node_id_to_label(src)
        label_dst = node_id_to_label(dst)
        
        # Get edge attributes
        attr = {
            'length': lengths.data[i],
            'voltage': voltages.data[i],
            'circuits': circuits.data[i]
        }
        
        # Add the edge with attributes
        G.add_edge(label_src, label_dst, **attr)

# Done!
print(f"Graph with {G.number_of_nodes()} nodes and {G.number_of_edges()} edges created.")

Graph with 5485 nodes and 7943 edges created.

import networkx as nx

# Assuming `G` is the NetworkX graph you have created
# Get the connected components (clusters) in the graph
connected_components = list(nx.connected_components(G))

# Filter clusters that have exactly 2 nodes
two_node_clusters = [component for component in connected_components if len(component) == 2]

# Print the number of 2-node clusters
print(f"Number of clusters with exactly 2 nodes: {len(two_node_clusters)}")

# Iterate through each 2-node cluster
for i, cluster in enumerate(two_node_clusters, 1):
    print(f"\nCluster {i} has {len(cluster)} nodes")

    # Get subgraph for this cluster
    subgraph = G.subgraph(cluster)

    # Find the longest edge (only one in this case)
    longest_edge_length = 0
    for u, v, data in subgraph.edges(data=True):
        edge_length = data.get('length', 0)  # Get the length attribute (or 0 if not present)
        longest_edge_length = max(longest_edge_length, edge_length)

    # Pick one node from the cluster
    one_node = next(iter(cluster))

    print(f"The longest edge in this cluster has a length of {longest_edge_length / 1000:.2f} km")
    print(f"One of the nodes in this cluster is: {one_node}")

#Creates a normal NetworkX Graph nG (no multiple edges per same node pair) FOR VISUAL PURPOSES ONLY

import networkx as nx
import numpy as np
from scipy.sparse import load_npz

# Load the sparse matrices
lengths = load_npz('/Users/kobabendiks/Desktop/UNI/Bachelor Thesis/Datasets/Transmission/entsoe/Links Edited/Matrices/PowerLinesMatrix_length.npz')
voltages = load_npz('/Users/kobabendiks/Desktop/UNI/Bachelor Thesis/Datasets/Transmission/entsoe/Links Edited/Matrices/PowerLinesMatrix_voltage.npz')
circuits = load_npz('/Users/kobabendiks/Desktop/UNI/Bachelor Thesis/Datasets/Transmission/entsoe/Links Edited/Matrices/PowerLinesMatrix_circuits.npz')

# Create an empty MultiGraph to support multiple edges between nodes
nG = nx.Graph()

# Convert node ID to label (row;col format)
def node_id_to_label(node_id, grid_width=5563):
    row = node_id // grid_width
    col = node_id % grid_width
    return f"[{row};{col}]"

# Add edges to the graph, skipping mirrored duplicates
for i in range(lengths.nnz):
    src = lengths.row[i]
    dst = lengths.col[i]
    
    # Skip one direction of symmetric matrix (to avoid duplication)
    if src < dst:
        label_src = node_id_to_label(src)
        label_dst = node_id_to_label(dst)
        
        # Get edge attributes
        attr = {
            'length': lengths.data[i],
            'voltage': voltages.data[i],
            'circuits': circuits.data[i]
        }
        
        # Add the edge with attributes
        nG.add_edge(label_src, label_dst, **attr)

# Done!
print(f"Graph with {nG.number_of_nodes()} nodes and {nG.number_of_edges()} edges created.")

#Visualisation

import networkx as nx
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Get node positions (convert labels back to row, column positions)
def get_node_position(node_label):
    # The node label is in the format "[row;col]"
    row, col = map(int, node_label.strip("[]").split(";"))
    return (col, row)  # (x, y) position: (col, row)

# Create a dictionary of node positions
pos = {node: get_node_position(node) for node in nG.nodes()}

# Plot the graph
plt.figure(figsize=(11, 10))

# Draw nodes and edges
nx.draw_networkx_nodes(nG, pos, node_size = 1, node_color='blue', alpha = 1.0)
nx.draw_networkx_edges(nG, pos, width=0.5, edge_color='black')

# Add labels (optional, for nodes with their coordinates)
# nx.draw_networkx_labels(G, pos, font_size=8, font_color='black')

# Title and axis labels
#plt.title("Transmission Network - Power Lines (Substation Connections) with True Node Positions")
#plt.xlabel("Column Index")
#plt.ylabel("Row Index")

# Invert Y-axis to match the coordinate system
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()

# Show grid
plt.grid(False)

# Show the plot
plt.show()

# Visualisation

import networkx as nx
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Get node positions (convert labels back to row, column positions)
def get_node_position(node_label):
    # The node label is in the format "[row;col]"
    row, col = map(int, node_label.strip("[]").split(";"))
    return (col, row)  # (x, y) position: (col, row)

# Create a dictionary of node positions
pos = {node: get_node_position(node) for node in nG.nodes()}

# Plot the graph
plt.figure(figsize=(13, 10))

# Draw nodes and edges
nx.draw_networkx_nodes(nG, pos, node_size=1, node_color='blue', alpha=1.0)
nx.draw_networkx_edges(nG, pos, width=0.5, edge_color='black')

# Add labels (optional)
# nx.draw_networkx_labels(nG, pos, font_size=8, font_color='black')

# Title
plt.title("Transmission Network - Power Lines (Substation Connections) with True Node Positions")

# Set axis limits
plt.xlim(0, 5563)
plt.ylim(0, 4478)

# Invert Y-axis to match coordinate system
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()

# Set axis ticks every 1000 units
plt.xticks(np.arange(0, 5564, 1000))
plt.yticks(np.arange(0, 4479, 1000))

# Show grid
plt.grid(True)

# Show the plot
plt.show()

import networkx as nx
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# --- Get all connected components ---
connected_components = list(nx.connected_components(nG))

# --- Identify specific components ---
largest_cc = max(connected_components, key=len)
size_13_ccs = [cc for cc in connected_components if len(cc) == 13]
size_146_ccs = [cc for cc in connected_components if len(cc) == 146]

# --- Select the first size 146 component if multiple exist ---
if size_146_ccs:
    size_146_cc = size_146_ccs[0]
else:
    size_146_cc = set()

# --- Combine all components to visualize ---
components_to_show = [largest_cc] + size_13_ccs
if size_146_cc:
    components_to_show.append(size_146_cc)

graphs_to_plot = [nG.subgraph(cc).copy() for cc in components_to_show]

# --- Visualization ---
plt.figure(figsize=(13, 10))

colors = (
    ['blue'] +                          # Largest component
    ['red'] * len(size_13_ccs) +       # Size-13 components
    (['green'] if size_146_cc else []) # Size-146 component
)

for G_sub, color in zip(graphs_to_plot, colors):
    def get_node_position(node_label):
        row, col = map(int, node_label.strip("[]").split(";"))
        return (col, row)

    pos = {node: get_node_position(node) for node in G_sub.nodes()}
    nx.draw_networkx_nodes(G_sub, pos, node_size=5, node_color=color, alpha=0.4)
    nx.draw_networkx_edges(G_sub, pos, width=0.5, edge_color='black')

# --- Labels and layout ---
plt.title("Transmission Network - Largest Cluster + Size 13 + Size 146 Components")
plt.xlabel("Column Index")
plt.ylabel("Row Index")
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

import networkx as nx
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# --- Get all connected components ---
connected_components = list(nx.connected_components(nG))

# --- Identify largest cluster and size-2 clusters ---
largest_cc = max(connected_components, key=len)
size_2_ccs = [cc for cc in connected_components if len(cc) == 2]

# --- Combine components to show ---
components_to_show = [largest_cc] + size_2_ccs
graphs_to_plot = [nG.subgraph(cc).copy() for cc in components_to_show]

# --- Visualization ---
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))

colors = (
    ['white'] +               # Largest cluster
    ['red'] * len(size_2_ccs)  # Clusters of size 2
)

for G_sub, color in zip(graphs_to_plot, colors):
    def get_node_position(node_label):
        row, col = map(int, node_label.strip("[]").split(";"))
        return (col, row)

    pos = {node: get_node_position(node) for node in G_sub.nodes()}
    nx.draw_networkx_nodes(G_sub, pos, node_size=5, node_color=color, alpha=0.4)
    nx.draw_networkx_edges(G_sub, pos, width=0.5, edge_color='black')

# --- Labels and layout ---
plt.title("Transmission Network - Largest Cluster + All Clusters of Size 2")
plt.xlabel("Column Index")
plt.ylabel("Row Index")
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
